## ABSOLUTE CODE GENERATION RULES

### 1. NO BUSINESS LOGIC MAY IMPORT INFRASTRUCTURE DIRECTLY

NEVER generate this pattern inside a service, use-case, or domain file:

```typescript
// FORBIDDEN in any service/domain/use-case file
import Stripe from "stripe";
import sgMail from "@sendgrid/mail";
import bcrypt from "bcrypt";
import { Pool } from "pg";
import jwt from "jsonwebtoken";
```

ALWAYS generate this pattern instead:

```typescript
// CORRECT â€” business logic depends on abstraction
import { IPaymentGateway } from "../interfaces/IPaymentGateway";
import { IEmailService } from "../interfaces/IEmailService";
import { IPasswordService } from "../interfaces/IPasswordService";
import { IUserRepository } from "../interfaces/IUserRepository";
import { ITokenService } from "../interfaces/ITokenService";
```

The infrastructure import belongs ONLY in the implementation file:

```typescript
// CORRECT â€” infrastructure lives here only
// src/infrastructure/payment/StripeGateway.ts
import Stripe from 'stripe';
export class StripeGateway implements IPaymentGateway { ... }
```

### 2. NO NEW KEYWORD INSIDE BUSINESS CLASSES

NEVER generate this:

```typescript
class OrderService {
  private repo = new PostgresOrderRepository(); // FORBIDDEN
  private emailer = new SendGridEmailer(); // FORBIDDEN
  private gateway = new StripeGateway(); // FORBIDDEN
}
```

ALWAYS generate this:

```typescript
class OrderService {
  constructor(
    private readonly repo: IOrderRepository, // INJECTED
    private readonly emailer: IEmailService, // INJECTED
    private readonly gateway: IPaymentGateway, // INJECTED
  ) {}
}
```

EXCEPTION â€” these MAY be instantiated directly (same boundary, no infrastructure):

```typescript
// These are pure logic â€” same actor, no external dependencies
const validator = new OrderValidator();
const formatter = new CurrencyFormatter();
const mapper = new OrderMapper();
```

### 3. ORCHESTRATORS MUST CONTAIN ZERO IMPLEMENTATION DETAILS

Any function named *Controller, *Handler, \*Orchestrator, or any custom hook (useFeature)
must read like a business document. It coordinates. It does not implement.

FORBIDDEN in an orchestrator:

```typescript
// FORBIDDEN â€” implementation detail in orchestrator
async function handleCheckout(req, res) {
  const hashed = await bcrypt.hash(password, 12); // NO
  const token = jwt.sign({ userId }, secret); // NO
  await db.query("INSERT INTO orders VALUES (...)"); // NO
  await sgMail.send({ to: email, subject: "Order..." }); // NO
}
```

REQUIRED orchestrator shape:

```typescript
// CORRECT â€” reads like the business story
async function handleCheckout(req: Request, res: Response) {
  const cart = await cartService.validateAndReserve(cartId, userId);
  const pricing = await pricingService.calculate(cart);
  const payment = await paymentGateway.charge(pricing.total, paymentToken);
  const order = await orderRepository.create(cart, payment);
  await notificationService.sendOrderConfirmation(userId, order);
  await analyticsService.track("order_placed", { orderId: order.id });
  return order;
}
```

### 4. EVERY INTERFACE MUST USE DOMAIN LANGUAGE

FORBIDDEN â€” infrastructure leaking into abstraction:

```typescript
interface IUserRepository {
  executeRawQuery(sql: string): Promise<any>; // FORBIDDEN
  beginPostgresTransaction(): Promise<void>; // FORBIDDEN
  getConnectionPool(): Pool; // FORBIDDEN
}
```

REQUIRED â€” domain language only:

```typescript
interface IUserRepository {
  findById(id: string): Promise<User | null>;
  findByEmail(email: string): Promise<User | null>;
  save(user: User): Promise<User>;
  delete(userId: string): Promise<void>;
}
```

### 5. NO GROWING IF/ELSE OR SWITCH ON TYPE

FORBIDDEN â€” OCP violation that grows:

```typescript
function processPayment(method: string, amount: number) {
  if (method === "stripe") {
    // stripe logic
  } else if (method === "paypal") {
    // paypal logic
  } else if (method === "braintree") {
    // new variant = modifying this file
    // braintree logic
  }
}
```

REQUIRED â€” strategy pattern with registry:

```typescript
// Each variant is its own file. processPayment never changes.
interface IPaymentStrategy {
  charge(amount: number): Promise<PaymentResult>;
}

class PaymentService {
  constructor(private readonly strategies: Map<string, IPaymentStrategy>) {}

  async process(method: string, amount: number): Promise<PaymentResult> {
    const strategy = this.strategies.get(method);
    if (!strategy) throw new Error(`Unknown payment method: ${method}`);
    return strategy.charge(amount);
  }
}
```

### 6. FRONTEND â€” HOOKS ARE ORCHESTRATORS, COMPONENTS ARE RENDERERS

FORBIDDEN â€” logic inside a component:

```tsx
// FORBIDDEN â€” component doing too much
function LoginForm() {
  const handleSubmit = async () => {
    const res = await fetch("/api/auth/login", {
      // NO â€” direct HTTP
      method: "POST",
      body: JSON.stringify({ email, password }),
    });
    localStorage.setItem("token", res.token); // NO â€” storage logic
    if (!email.includes("@")) return; // NO â€” validation logic
  };
}
```

REQUIRED â€” component renders, hook orchestrates:

```tsx
// CORRECT â€” component only renders and collects input
function LoginForm() {
  const { login, isLoading, error } = useAuth();
  return (
    <form
      onSubmit={(e) => {
        e.preventDefault();
        login({ email, password });
      }}
    >
      {error && <ErrorMessage message={error} />}
      <button disabled={isLoading}>Login</button>
    </form>
  );
}

// CORRECT â€” hook orchestrates, knows nothing about HTTP or storage internals
function useAuth() {
  const [isLoading, setIsLoading] = useState(false);
  const [error, setError] = useState<string | null>(null);

  const login = useCallback(async (credentials: LoginCredentials) => {
    const validationError = validateLoginInput(credentials); // validation layer
    if (validationError) {
      setError(validationError);
      return false;
    }
    const response = await authApi.login(credentials); // api layer
    await tokenStorage.store(response.tokens); // storage layer
    setUser(response.user); // state layer
    return true;
  }, []);

  return { login, isLoading, error };
}
```

### 7. EVERY MODULE BOUNDARY MUST HAVE A JUSTIFIED COMMENT

When generating any class, service, repository, or hook, include this comment block:

```typescript
/**
 * RESPONSIBILITY: [One sentence â€” what this module does]
 * OWNER: [Which actor/team owns this â€” who sends change requests]
 * BOUNDARY REASON: [Why this is a separate module â€” what change scenario justifies the boundary]
 * CHANGES WHEN: [Specific realistic scenario that would cause this file to change]
 */
```

Example:

```typescript
/**
 * RESPONSIBILITY: Verifies and issues access + refresh token pairs
 * OWNER: Infrastructure team
 * BOUNDARY REASON: Token strategy (JWT format, signing algorithm, lifetime) changes
 *                  on infrastructure team's timeline, independently of business logic
 * CHANGES WHEN: Switching from JWT to opaque tokens, adding token rotation,
 *               changing signing algorithm or token lifetime policies
 */
export class TokenService implements ITokenService {
```

### 8. LSP â€” ALL FOUR CONTRACT COMPONENTS MUST BE HONORED

When generating an interface implementation, always verify all four:

```typescript
// When implementing any interface, add this verification comment:
/**
 * LSP CONTRACT VERIFICATION for [InterfaceName]:
 * âœ“ Accepts: [same or wider input types than interface promises]
 * âœ“ Returns: [same or narrower return types than interface promises]
 * âœ“ Throws: [only exceptions defined in interface contract]
 * âœ“ Side effects: [system state changes match what interface implies]
 * âœ“ Sequences: [save() then findById() returns saved entity]
 */
```

FORBIDDEN â€” silent no-ops (worst LSP violation):

```typescript
class ReadOnlyCache implements ICache {
  set(key: string, value: unknown): void {
    // do nothing  â† FORBIDDEN â€” breaks side effect contract silently
  }
  delete(key: string): void {
    // do nothing  â† FORBIDDEN â€” caller assumes key is gone after this
  }
}
```

### 9. ISP â€” SPLIT ONLY WHEN A CLIENT IS CONCRETELY HARMED

Before splitting an interface, add this decision comment:

```typescript
/**
 * ISP DECISION: Why this interface is split
 * Specific client harmed: [name the client]
 * Concrete harm: [forced to stub X methods / recompiled on unrelated changes]
 * Result after split: [client's dependency is leaner and safer]
 */
```

Do NOT split an interface just because a client "doesn't call" some methods.
Split only when the client is forced to implement, stub, or be unnecessarily coupled.

### 10. NO ENVIRONMENT CHECKS IN BUSINESS LOGIC

FORBIDDEN:

```typescript
class UserService {
  async sendEmail(email: string) {
    if (process.env.NODE_ENV === 'test') return; // FORBIDDEN
    await sgMail.send(...);
  }
}
```

REQUIRED â€” inject environment-appropriate implementation:

```typescript
// In tests: inject MockEmailService
// In production: inject SendGridEmailService
// UserService never knows which one it has
class UserService {
  constructor(private readonly emailService: IEmailService) {}

  async sendEmail(email: string) {
    await this.emailService.send(email); // always calls the injected one
  }
}
```

