## WHAT GOOD CODE COMMENTS LOOK LIKE

Every non-obvious architectural decision must have a comment explaining WHY, not WHAT:

```typescript
// BAD â€” describes what the code does (obvious from reading it)
// Create a new user
const user = await userRepository.create(userData);

// GOOD â€” explains the architectural decision
// UserRepository is injected â€” this service never imports the DB directly.
// Switching from PostgreSQL to MongoDB requires zero changes to this file.
const user = await this.userRepository.create(userData);

// GOOD â€” explains a boundary decision
// tokenService is the ONLY file in this codebase that imports 'jsonwebtoken'.
// All other files call tokenService.issue() and tokenService.verify().
// Token strategy changes (algorithm, format, lifetime) never propagate beyond this file.
const tokens = await this.tokenService.issue(identity);
```
